<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-quadratic-equations-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quadratic Equations in Real-Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Apply quadratic equations to real life situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that quadratic equations can model real-world phenomena such as projectile motion, area optimization, and profit/loss scenarios.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Set up and solve quadratic equations from word problems using factorisation, the quadratic formula, or completing the square.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply quadratic equations to solve problems in physics (projectile motion), geometry (area problems), and business (profit optimization).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/quadratic-equations-in-real-life.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/step-by-step-guide_quadratic-equations-in-real-life.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


    <p xml:id="auto_5jfy1mvy">
        <em><term>Quadratic equations</term></em> are a type of mathematical equation that can be used to describe many different <em><term>real-life</term></em> situations. 
        Whether you're throwing a ball in the air, trying to maximize the area of a garden, or calculating profits for a business, 
        quadratic equations can help solve problems that involve relationships with squared terms.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_vl3adg2v">
        In this section, we will learn how to recognize real-life situations that can be modeled by quadratic equations, 
        how to set them up, and how to solve them step by step.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_d0ju0h1e">
        A quadratic equation is an equation that can be written in the form:
        <me>
            ax^2 + bx + c = 0
        </me>
        where, 
        <ul xml:id="auto_mtv1sl62">
            <li xml:id="auto_kdh2lp4t">
                <p xml:id="auto_sdlxxeuw">
                    <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are real numbers or constants,
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ukgc8qca">
                <p xml:id="auto_ivunewjj">
                    <m>x</m> is the unknown variable
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_mhg9q0c6">
                <p xml:id="auto_1hg82hd3">
                    and <m>a \neq 0</m> beacuse if <m>a</m> is <m>0,</m> it would not be a quadratic
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_q276t54c">
        Quadratic equations show up in many situations, especially when something is changing in a way that involves squares (like height, area, or profit).
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_8cw1wvk9">
        Lets take a look at some of the situations <em><term>Quadratic Equations</term></em> is involved in real life situations.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_pk7n0x9f">
        <m>1. \, Projectile \, Motion (Throwing \, a \, Ball).</m>
    </p>
    <image source="projectile.png" width="70%">
        <shortdescription>projectile</shortdescription>
    </image>
    <p xml:id="auto_azc36qm2">
        One of the most common real-life situations for quadratic equations is <term>projectile motion</term>, such as when you throw a ball in the air. 
        The height of the ball over time can be described by a quadratic equation.
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Real-World Quadratic Discovery
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Give each group one of 4 scenario cards:
                    <ol>
                        <li><p><q>A ball is kicked upward at <m>20 \text{ m/s}</m> and reaches height <m>h(t) = 20t - 5t^2</m>. When does it land?</q></p></li>
                        <li><p><q>A rectangular field has area <m>120 \text{ m}^2</m>, and the length is <m>2 \text{ m}</m> more than the width. Find the dimensions.</q></p></li>
                        <li><p><q>A company's profit is <m>P(x) = -2x^2 + 40x - 150</m> where <m>x</m> = items sold (thousands). Find the break-even points.</q></p></li>
                        <li><p><q>An object is dropped from <m>80 \text{ m}</m>: <m>h(t) = 80 - 5t^2</m>. When does it hit the ground?</q></p></li>
                    </ol>
                    Each group: form the equation, identify variables, and attempt to solve.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, asking probing questions: <q>What does <m>x</m> represent?</q>, <q>How do you form the equation?</q>, <q>What is a reasonable answer?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <p>
            <alert>Work in Groups. Each group receives a different real-life scenario:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Scenario Cards:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="Group 1">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Projectile Motion:</alert> A ball is thrown upward from the ground with an initial velocity of <m>20 m/s</m>. Its height after <m>t</m> seconds is <m>h(t) = 20t - 5t^2</m>. When does the ball hit the ground?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Area Problem:</alert> A farmer wants to fence a rectangular garden using <m>60</m> meters of fencing. What dimensions give the maximum area?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert> Business Profit:</alert> A company's profit is <m>P(x) = −2x^2 + 40x - 150</m>, where <m>x</m> is the number of items sold. How many items must be sold to break even?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Falling Object:</alert> A stone is dropped from a <m>45</m>> meter cliff. Its height is <m>h(t) = 45 - 5t^2</m>>. When does it hit the ground?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Group Tasks:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Identify the quadratic equation in your scenario
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What does each variable represent?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Try to solve the problem
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What does your answer mean in real life?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <term>Discussion Questions:</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                       What makes these problems "quadratic"? 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Why do some answers need to be rejected (negative time, negative length)?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        What patterns do you notice across different scenarios?
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Circulate among groups, asking probing questions. Help students identify the quadratic structure in each problem. Use student discoveries to bridge to formal instruction.
        </p>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Present common applications and a systematic problem-solving approach for real-life quadratic equations.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Present the Common Applications table:
                </p>
                <table>
                    <title>Common Applications of Quadratic Equations</title>
                    <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium" halign="left">
                        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                            <cell>Application</cell>
                            <cell>Typical Equation Form</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Projectile Motion</cell>
                            <cell><m>h(t) = at^2 + bt + c</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Area Problems</cell>
                            <cell><m>l \times w = A</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>Profit / Revenue</cell>
                            <cell><m>P(x) = ax^2 + bx + c</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>
                    Introduce the 5 Problem-Solving Steps:
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Identify the variable</p></li>
                        <li><p>Form the equation</p></li>
                        <li><p>Solve by factorising or using the quadratic formula</p></li>
                        <li><p>Check both solutions</p></li>
                        <li><p>Reject non-physical solutions (negative lengths, negative time)</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Note:</alert> Always check that answers make physical sense.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Walk through the table and steps, connecting each to the scenarios explored in Phase 1. Emphasise the importance of interpreting solutions in context.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <alert>What are Real-Life Quadratics?</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
           Quadratic equations can describe many real-life situations: 
        </p>
        <p>
            Throwing a ball in the air (projectile motion)
        </p>
        <p>
           Maximizing the area of a garden (optimization) 
        </p>
        <p>
            Calculating profits for a business (economics)
        </p>
        <p>
            Objects falling under gravity (physics)
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>The Standard Form:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            A quadratic equation has the form: <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>, where:
        </p>
        <p>
           <m>a, b,</m> and <m>c</m> are real numbers (constants) 
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>x</m> is the unknown variable
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>a \neq 0</m> (if <m>a = 0</m>, it's not quadratic)
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Common Real-Life Applications:</alert>
        </p>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Application</cell>
                <cell>Typical Equation</cell>
                <cell>Form What We Find</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Projectile Motion</cell><cell><m>h(t) = -5t^2 + v_ot + h_o</m></cell>
                <cell>Time to hit ground, max height</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Area Problems</cell>
                <cell><m>A = x(\frac{p}{2}- x)</m></cell>
                <cell>Dimensions for max area</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Profit / Revenue</cell>
                <cell><m>P(x) = ax^2 + bx + c</m></cell>
                <cell>Break-even point, max profit</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p>
            <alert>Problem-Solving Steps:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            1. Read the problem and identify what's being asked
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Define variables (what does x represent?)
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Set up the quadratic equation
        </p>
        <p>
            4. Solve using factorisation, quadratic formula, or completing the square
        </p>
        <p>
            5. Interpret the answer in context (reject impossible values)
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Remember:</alert>  Always check if your answer makes sense! Negative time or negative lengths are usually not valid in real-life problems
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Apply the problem-solving steps to a worked example involving a falling object.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Worked Example:</alert> A rock is dropped from a height of <m>50 \text{ m}</m>. Its height is given by <m>h(t) = 50 - 5t^2</m>. When does it hit the ground?
                </p>
                <p>
                    When <m>h = 0</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>50 - 5t^2 \amp= 0</mrow>
                        <mrow>5t^2 \amp= 50</mrow>
                        <mrow>t^2 \amp= 10</mrow>
                        <mrow>t \amp= \sqrt{10} \approx 3.16 \text{ s}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Reject <m>t = -\sqrt{10}</m> as time cannot be negative.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Guide learners through the worked example step by step, reinforcing each of the 5 problem-solving steps. Encourage learners to explain why the negative solution is rejected.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_pqtwohrx">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_7l04ypml">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bzv6trti">
                A rock is dropped from a height of <m>50</m> meters. 
                Its height above the ground at time <m>t</m> is given by
                <me>
                    h(t) = 5t^2 + 50.
                </me>
                 Use factorization to determine how long it will take for the rock to reach the ground.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_xle0if65">
                The height of the rock above the ground is given by:
                <me>
                    h(t) = -5t^2 + 50
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_z0z3bspu">
                To find when the rock reaches the ground, set <m>h(t) = 0</m>:
                <me>
                    -5t^2 + 50 = 0
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_eswtiuhi">
                Simplify the equation:
                <me>
                    -5t^2 = -50
                </me>
                <me>
                    t^2 = 10
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_i7lhja2n">
                Solve for <m>t</m>:
                <me>
                    t = \pm \sqrt{10}
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3i0xg61q">
                Since time cannot be negative, <m>t = \sqrt{10}</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_tyw8fkac">
                Therefore, the rock will take approximately <m>\sqrt{10} \approx 3.16</m> seconds to reach the ground.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <p xml:id="auto_sl1bdhc6">
        <m>2. \, Maximizing \, Area \, (Optimization \, Problem).</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_fy4rhvuz">
        Quadratic equations are also used in optimization problems. 
        These are problems where you want to maximize or minimize something, like the area of a garden.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="auto_7ckxddqm">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_9pnhznpi">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_196qsboy">
                The length of a rectangle is <m>3</m> meters more than its width. If the area of the rectangle is <m>54</m> square meters, 
                find the dimensions of the rectangle by factoring the quadratic equation.
            </p>
            <image source="optimization_problems.png" width="70%">
                <shortdescription>optimization problems</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>            
            <p xml:id="auto_xhu77o1p">
                Let the width of the rectangle be <m>x</m>. Then the length is <m>x + 3</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_6gcbkocz">
                The area of the rectangle is given by:
                <me>
                    x(x + 3) = 54
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_748w0cx0">
                Expand and rearrange into standard quadratic form:
                <me>
                    x^2 + 3x - 54 = 0
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xw4b2kxj">
                Factorize the quadratic equation:
                <me>
                    (x + 9)(x - 6) = 0
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_kynhxft6">
                Solve for <m>x</m>:
                <me>
                    x = -9 \, \text{or} \, x = 6
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_lpgv146r">
                Since width cannot be negative, <m>x = 6</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_35io71nf">
                The dimensions of the rectangle are:
                <me>
                    \text{Width} = 6 \, \text{meters}, \, \text{Length} = 6 + 3 = 9 \, \text{meters}.
                </me>
                Since the width cannot be negative, the width is <m>6</m> meters, and lenght is <m>6 + 3 = 9</m> meters.
            </p>
        </solution>
    
    </example>

    <p xml:id="auto_sryz7uso">
        <m>3. Business \, Applications (Profit \, Function)</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_izkv63k3">
        Businesses often use quadratic equations to model their profit. 
        For example, the profit a company makes from selling a product can be modeled by a quadratic equation.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="auto_n406xaqu">

        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_yeptlvkg">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_10gmlwum">
                A company's profit <m>P(x)</m> from selling <m>x</m> units of a product is given by the equation:
                <me>
                    P(x) = -x^2 + 15x - 50
                </me>
                Find how many units the company needs to sell to have no profit (i.e., when the profit is zero).
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_cxb08oex">
                To find when the company has no profit, set <m>P(x) = 0</m>:
                <me>
                    -x^2 + 20x - 50 = 0
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_m10yvm6x">
                Multiply through by <m>-1</m> to simplify:
                <me>
                    x^2 - 20x + 50 = 0
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_90vmpoyz">
                Factorize the quadratic equation:
                <me>
                    (x - 10)(x - 5) = 0
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_fvrri6dl">
                Solve for <m>x</m>:
                <me>
                    x = 10 or x = 5
                </me>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_tncgtes7">
                Therefore, the company will have no profit when it sells either <m>5</m> units or <m>10</m> units.
            </p>
        </solution>

    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment / Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Assess learners' ability to set up and solve real-life quadratic equation problems independently.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Problems</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>A ball is thrown upward at <m>15 \text{ m/s}</m>. Its height is <m>h(t) = 15t - 5t^2</m>. When does it reach <m>10 \text{ m}</m>?</p></li>
                        <li><p>A rectangular room has area <m>48 \text{ m}^2</m>. The length is <m>2 \text{ m}</m> more than the width. Find the dimensions.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>P(x) = -x^2 + 12x - 20</m>. Find the break-even points.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>15t - 5t^2 \amp= 10</mrow>
                                    <mrow>5t^2 - 15t + 10 \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>t^2 - 3t + 2 \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>(t - 1)(t - 2) \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>t = 1 \text{ s} \amp\text{ or } t = 2 \text{ s}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>w(w + 2) \amp= 48</mrow>
                                    <mrow>w^2 + 2w - 48 \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>(w + 8)(w - 6) \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>w = 6 \text{ m}, \amp\text{ length} = 8 \text{ m}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>-x^2 + 12x - 20 \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x^2 - 12x + 20 \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>(x - 2)(x - 10) \amp= 0</mrow>
                                    <mrow>x = 2 \amp\text{ or } x = 10 \text{ (thousands)}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-application-of-quadratic-equations-to-real-life-situations">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_nnguam4z">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_xxw3ru1b">
                    A stone is thrown into the air from a height of <m>4</m> meters with an initial velocity of <m>8</m> meters per second. 
                            The height of the stone at time <m>t</m> is given by:
                            <me>
                                h(t) = -5t^2 + 8t + 4
                            </me>
                            Find when the stone reaches the ground.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    To find when the stone reaches the ground, set <m>h(t) = 0</m>:
                    <me>
                        -5t^2 + 8t + 4 = 0
                    </me>
                    Multiply through by <m>-1</m> to simplify:
                    <me>
                        5t^2 - 8t - 4 = 0
                    </me>
                    Factorize the quadratic equation:
                    <me>
                        (5t + 2)(t - 2) = 0
                    </me>
                    Solve for <m>t</m>:
                    <me>
                        t = -\frac{2}{5} \, \text{or} \, t = 2
                    </me>
                    Since time cannot be negative, the stone will reach the ground after <m>2</m> seconds.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_9g17jydq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_1i0g67ss">
                    A farmer has <m>200</m> meters of fencing. He wants to build a rectangular garden. 
                    The length is <m>50</m> meters longer than the width. What should the dimensions be to maximize the area?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Let the width of the garden be <m>x</m>. Then the length is <m>x + 50</m>.
                    The perimeter of the rectangle is given by:
                    <me>
                        2(x + (x + 50)) = 200
                    </me>
                    Simplify and solve for <m>x</m>:
                    <me>
                        4x + 100 = 200
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        4x = 100
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        x = 25
                    </me>
                    Therefore, the width of the garden should be <m>25</m> meters, and the length should be <m>25 + 50 = 75</m> meters to maximize the area.
                  </p>
             </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_qq1pnq3b">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ahkz68b9">
                    A school's profit function is given by:
                    <me>
                        P(x) = -x^2 + 30x - 100
                    </me>
                    Find the number of units the company must sell to achieve zero profit.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    To find when the company has zero profit, set <m>P(x) = 0</m>:
                    <me>
                        -x^2 + 30x - 100 = 0
                    </me>
                    Multiply through by <m>-1</m> to simplify:
                    <me>
                        x^2 - 30x + 100 = 0
                    </me>
                    Factorize the quadratic equation:
                    <me>
                        (x - 20)(x - 10) = 0
                    </me>
                    Solve for <m>x</m>:
                    <me>
                        x = 20 \, \text{or} \, x = 10
                    </me>
                    Therefore, the company will have zero profit when it sells either <m>10</m> units or <m>20</m> units.
                </p>
              </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_oe9nwguq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_sh8nunks">
                    A water fountain shoots water into the air, and its height at any time <m>t</m> (in seconds) is given by the equation:
                    <me>
                        h(t)  = -4.9t^2 + 15t + 2
                    </me>
                    Find the time it will take for the water to return to the ground (i.e., when <m>h(t)=0</m>).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    To find when the water returns to the ground, set <m>h(t) = 0</m>:
                    <me>
                        -4.9t^2 + 15t + 2 = 0
                    </me>
                    Multiply through by <m>-1</m> to simplify:
                    <me>
                        4.9t^2 - 15t - 2 = 0
                    </me>
                    Factorize the quadratic equation:
                    <me>
                        (4.9t + 1)(t - \frac{2}{4.9}) = 0
                    </me>
                    Solve for <m>t</m>:
                    <me>
                        t = -\frac{1}{4.9} \, \text{or} \, t = \frac{2}{4.9}
                    </me>
                    Since time cannot be negative, the water will return to the ground after approximately <m>\frac{2}{4.9} \approx 0.41</m> seconds.
                </p>
                </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_yau8vav5">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_kbqx0rwh">
                    Solve the following quadratic equation:
                    <me>
                        x^2 - 7x + 12 = 0
                    </me>
                    Find the value of <m>x.</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                   <p>
                      Factorize the quadratic equation:
                     <me>
                        (x - 3)(x - 4) = 0
                     </me>
                     Solve for <m>x</m>:
                     <me>
                        x = 3 \, \text{or} \, x = 4
                     </me>
                     Therefore, the values of <m>x</m> that satisfy the equation are <m>3</m> and <m>4.</m>
                  </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_6rtxzfkq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_a5allk10">
                    A company finds that the revenue <m>R(x)</m> it generates from selling <m>x</m> units of a product is given by the quadratic equation:
                    <me>
                        R(x) = 2x^2 + 40x
                    </me>
                    Find the number of units <m>x</m> that the company needs to sell to maximize its revenue.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                  <p>
                     To find the number of units that maximizes revenue, we can use the formula for the vertex of a parabola given by a quadratic equation in the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c</m>, which is <m>x = -\frac{b}{2a}</m>.
                     In this case, <m>a = 2</m> and <m>b = 40</m>.
                     Substitute these values into the formula:
                     <me>
                        x = -\frac{40}{2 \cdot 2} = -\frac{40}{4} = -10
                     </me>
                     Since the number of units cannot be negative, we need to check the behavior of the quadratic function to determine if it opens upwards or downwards. 
                     Since <m>a &gt; 0</m>, the fuction opens upwards, meaning that the vertex represents a minimum point. 
                     Therefore, there is no maximum revenue in this case, and the company can increase its revenue indefinitely by selling more units.
                  </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_vt928oc2">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_47vyhwvd">
                    The path of a car is represented by the quadratic equation
                    <me>
                        y = 2x^2 - 8x,
                    </me>
                    where <m>x</m> represents time in seconds and <m>y</m> represents the car's position. 
                    Find the time when the car reaches its starting position by factorizing the equation.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                  <p>
                    To find when the car reaches its starting position, set <m>y = 0</m>:
                    <me>
                        2x^2 - 8x = 0
                    </me>
                    Factorize the equation:
                    <me>
                        2x(x - 4) = 0
                    </me>
                    Solve for <m>x</m>:
                    <me>
                        x = 0 \, \text{or} \, x = 4
                    </me>
                    Therefore, the car reaches its starting position at <m>0</m> seconds and again at <m>4</m> seconds.
                  </p>
             </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide equation templates with blanks for learners to fill in. Use diagrams and pictures to illustrate scenarios. Start with simpler problems where the answer is <m>h = 0</m> (e.g., when does the ball hit the ground?).</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all problems as described. Check all solutions for physical sense. Pair work on word problems to discuss and verify answers.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Multi-step problems requiring two equations, find maximum/minimum values using the vertex, and create their own real-life quadratic problems for classmates to solve.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A ball is thrown upward at <m>30 \text{ m/s}</m>: <m>h(t) = 30t - 5t^2</m>. When does it pass <m>40 \text{ m}</m>?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>30t - 5t^2 \amp= 40</mrow>
                            <mrow>5t^2 - 30t + 40 \amp= 0</mrow>
                            <mrow>t^2 - 6t + 8 \amp= 0</mrow>
                            <mrow>(t - 2)(t - 4) \amp= 0</mrow>
                            <mrow>t = 2 \text{ s (going up)}, \amp\quad t = 4 \text{ s (coming down)}</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the maximum area of a rectangle with perimeter <m>24 \text{ m}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>2l + 2w \amp= 24 \implies l = 12 - w</mrow>
                            <mrow>A \amp= w(12 - w) = -w^2 + 12w</mrow>
                            <mrow>\text{Max at } w \amp= -\frac{12}{2 \times (-1)} = 6</mrow>
                            <mrow>A \amp= 6(12 - 6) = 36 \text{ m}^2</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A ticket costs <m>\$10</m> and <m>200</m> people buy it. Each <m>\$1</m> increase loses <m>10</m> buyers. Find the price that maximises revenue.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>R \amp= (10 + x)(200 - 10x)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp= -10x^2 + 100x + 2000</mrow>
                            <mrow>\text{Max at } x \amp= -\frac{100}{2 \times (-10)} = 5</mrow>
                            <mrow>\text{Price} \amp= \$15, \quad R = \$2250</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
